1. Required Text - All text under the headings *Community Participation Guidelines and How to Report*, are required, and should not be altered.

Some examples of those can be found on the [Firefox Debugger](https://github.com/devtools-html/debugger.html/blob/master/CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md) project, and [Common Voice](https://github.com/mozilla/voice-web/blob/master/CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md). (The optional part is commented out in the [raw template file](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/mozilla/repo-templates/blob/master/templates/CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md), and will not be visible until you modify and uncomment that part.)

If you have any questions about this file, or Code of Conduct policies and procedures, please see [Mozilla-GitHub-Standards](https://wiki.mozilla.org/GitHub/Repository_Requirements) or email Mozilla-GitHub-Standards+CoC@mozilla.com.

pulltitle: Use pipenv for controlling the Python virtual environment
pullsbody:
This locks the entire Python dependency graph so that a consistent environment can be used to run tests and generate the reports. I haven't modified the README.md for generating the reports because I wasn't able to test it. With [pipenv](https://pipenv.readthedocs.io/en/latest/) installed you *should* just be able to run `pipenv install` followed by your command, such as:

```
pipenv run python usage_report/usage_report.py --date 20180201 --lag-days 1 --no-output
```

For what it's worth, before making these changes, I had to interrupt `tox` as it was taking forever to install the `fx_usage_report` package. After these changes, I am able to run `tox` without any issues, and my environment should be identical to anyone else running this using pipenv.

Typically, the versions in `Pipfile` would not be pinned, but they are always pinned in `Pipfile.lock` (along with the transient dependencies). I didn't want to change the versions of the direct dependencies with this patch though. A followup could take care of this.

Note that it is necessary to pin moto (I picked the version available at the time `setup.py` was written) due to https://github.com/spulec/moto/issues/1800, which demonstrates the value in using a lock file for all dependencies.
pull_repo_desc: Deprecated - please see https://github.com/mozilla/firefox-public-data-report-etl for the current ETL powering Firefox Public Data Report
pull_commit_message: Use pipenv for controlling the Python virtual environment

pulltitle: (DO NOT MERGE) updated top10addons to enforce 10 unique addon names
pullsbody:
made the following changes for top10addons due to https://github.com/mozilla/Fx_Usage_Report/issues/51:

* for each addon (combination of `addon.id` and `addon.name`) per `addon.name`, keep only the most common one and get rid of the others. 
* get the top N addons from this filtered set, to ensure we have no `addon.name` collisions in our final data.

pulltitle: additional constraints for get_daily_avg_session and get_avg_intensity
pullsbody:
added additional constraints to avg daily use and intensity, to cap a day's session total to 24 hours and intensity to 1.0. 

i observed outliers were skewing the data up (since we are using a mean across users). 

we were capping individual ping's subsession length and active ticks at the daily max, but by aggregating per client over a day, we were exceeding that threshold. i suspect it's from multiple user -> single cid situations.
